[ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Clement for his important comments. All laboratories in the Americas should adopt the capability to make differential diagnoses that includes SEOV. Similarly, clinicians attending suspected or confirmed cases of hantavirus infection in the Americas should be aware of the clinical features of SEOV-HFRS such as renal involvement with easy dipstick urine evaluation of proteinuria/microhematuria. Distinguishing between infections of SEOV and other hantaviruses in the Americas is clinically important. SEOV infections are usually milder and of shorter duration. Infections in the Americas with Sin Nombre or Andes viruses can cause HCPS with case fatality rates of 30-40%. Knowing which hantavirus is the epidemiological agent in hantavirus cases in the Americas is epidemiologically important as well. The rodent host of SEOV is wild or domestic brown rats (_Rattus norvegicus_), which are widely distributed in the Americas and around the world. Other hantaviruses in the Americas have native, and often quite restricted, rodent hosts. Strategies for controlling these rodent reservoir hosts are different. Knowing which hantavirus is responsible for these human infections is important. - Mod.TY

